WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.768 --> 00:00:02.950
VICTORIA: Hello, everybody.

00:00:02.950 --> 00:00:05.620
Thanks so much for
coming to this talk

00:00:05.620 --> 00:00:10.810
by my wonderful friend James
who is also a first time author.

00:00:10.810 --> 00:00:13.250
I want to tell you three
quick things about James.

00:00:13.250 --> 00:00:17.080
The first is that James'
book is about the importance

00:00:17.080 --> 00:00:18.720
of experience.

00:00:18.720 --> 00:00:21.650
And I want to vouch for the
fact that this guy doesn't just

00:00:21.650 --> 00:00:23.940
talk the talk, he
walks the walk.

00:00:23.940 --> 00:00:28.250
James and I met 14 years--
ago almost to this day--

00:00:28.250 --> 00:00:33.881
on an overnight bus going from
Delhi to Rishikesh in India.

00:00:33.881 --> 00:00:35.630
For those of you who
don't know Rishikesh,

00:00:35.630 --> 00:00:38.046
it's supposed to be sort of
the yoga capital of the world,

00:00:38.046 --> 00:00:40.820
the Beatles went there to
see the Maharishi Mahesh,

00:00:40.820 --> 00:00:43.450
Jerry's ashes are
there, et cetera.

00:00:43.450 --> 00:00:45.740
And I was, of course, there
to go and check myself

00:00:45.740 --> 00:00:48.040
into an ashram to continue
to do the yoga that I

00:00:48.040 --> 00:00:49.190
was in love with.

00:00:49.190 --> 00:00:52.590
And James was there to learn
about this thing called yoga

00:00:52.590 --> 00:00:56.580
that he'd heard about but
didn't really know what it was.

00:00:56.580 --> 00:00:58.690
He said he was going to
be there for three days.

00:00:58.690 --> 00:01:00.790
And after we went
into this ashram,

00:01:00.790 --> 00:01:03.600
he sort of fell in
love with the Ashtanga,

00:01:03.600 --> 00:01:06.120
and the macrobiotic
diet, and the meditation,

00:01:06.120 --> 00:01:08.920
and the aura reading, and
even the homemade colonics,

00:01:08.920 --> 00:01:10.910
and basically,
decided to stay there

00:01:10.910 --> 00:01:12.680
for 30 days with
me, which is where

00:01:12.680 --> 00:01:14.050
we became such great friends.

00:01:14.050 --> 00:01:16.730
So this guy is the real deal.

00:01:16.730 --> 00:01:19.970
The second thing is that
when we were in India,

00:01:19.970 --> 00:01:23.020
James and I were
absolutely love struck.

00:01:23.020 --> 00:01:24.130
Not with each other.

00:01:24.130 --> 00:01:27.210
We actually both had
partners-- him in London

00:01:27.210 --> 00:01:30.110
and me in the States, and we're
no longer with these people--

00:01:30.110 --> 00:01:32.500
but we were so bored in
the ashram at night--

00:01:32.500 --> 00:01:35.100
absolutely nothing goes
on in an ashram at night--

00:01:35.100 --> 00:01:37.400
that we would write
these incredible love

00:01:37.400 --> 00:01:38.849
letters to our
significant others,

00:01:38.849 --> 00:01:40.390
and we would read
them to each other.

00:01:40.390 --> 00:01:41.920
That's how bored we were.

00:01:41.920 --> 00:01:44.920
And I can just tell you that he
is the most beautiful writer.

00:01:44.920 --> 00:01:48.910
So I'm so happy that 14 years
later, he has written a book.

00:01:48.910 --> 00:01:51.000
And the third
thing to tell you--

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:53.030
just because it will
endear him to you--

00:01:53.030 --> 00:01:56.171
is that James is about to become
a father for the second time.

00:01:56.171 --> 00:01:58.420
He didn't know if he would
be able to make it out here

00:01:58.420 --> 00:01:59.920
in time before his
wife gives birth.

00:01:59.920 --> 00:02:01.731
So I'm very happy
that he's here.

00:02:01.731 --> 00:02:02.355
Welcome, James.

00:02:08.526 --> 00:02:10.849
JAMES WALLMAN:
Thank you, Victoria.

00:02:10.849 --> 00:02:12.390
That's pretty funny
because I haven't

00:02:12.390 --> 00:02:14.247
heard that story for some time.

00:02:14.247 --> 00:02:16.330
Especially, the bit about
writing the love letters

00:02:16.330 --> 00:02:18.240
and reading them to each other.

00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:21.100
Because I've actually found some
I never got around to sending.

00:02:21.100 --> 00:02:23.810
And they are-- you know those
really embarrassing letters

00:02:23.810 --> 00:02:26.010
that you never sent
for good reason?

00:02:26.010 --> 00:02:28.010
So I'm touched that you
say I was a good writer,

00:02:28.010 --> 00:02:30.050
but I think I wasn't back then.

00:02:30.050 --> 00:02:32.380
But anyway, I appreciate
that very much.

00:02:32.380 --> 00:02:34.220
It's great to be back
in Mountain View.

00:02:34.220 --> 00:02:39.040
And I say back because I
lived in Palo Alto in 1997.

00:02:39.040 --> 00:02:41.710
And I have a strong
connection to Mountain View--

00:02:41.710 --> 00:02:43.900
a strong experiential
connection to Mountain View,

00:02:43.900 --> 00:02:46.300
actually-- because
when I was here,

00:02:46.300 --> 00:02:51.730
I learned how to scuba dive
with the Bayview Divers.

00:02:51.730 --> 00:02:54.350
Anyone learn to scuba
dive in Mountain View?

00:02:54.350 --> 00:02:55.260
I have the card.

00:02:55.260 --> 00:02:57.720
It's the card I've been using
on this trip to the States

00:02:57.720 --> 00:02:59.056
as my ID.

00:02:59.056 --> 00:03:00.680
So every time I was
in New York before,

00:03:00.680 --> 00:03:02.410
and I was going to buildings
like the Hearst Building,

00:03:02.410 --> 00:03:04.590
the Conde Nast Building,
the Time &amp; Life Building,

00:03:04.590 --> 00:03:05.660
and they want to see ID.

00:03:05.660 --> 00:03:09.390
And I gave them the ID
of this scuba diving card

00:03:09.390 --> 00:03:12.560
I have from when I
was in my early 20s--

00:03:12.560 --> 00:03:15.833
I mean I look completely
different, obviously-- Anyway,

00:03:15.833 --> 00:03:17.416
and that was-- I
checked this out-- it

00:03:17.416 --> 00:03:18.540
was before Google started.

00:03:18.540 --> 00:03:20.040
It was a year before
Google started,

00:03:20.040 --> 00:03:21.425
so I was here first, all right.

00:03:24.520 --> 00:03:25.995
Thank you for
coming, first of all.

00:03:25.995 --> 00:03:28.134
I really appreciate it.

00:03:28.134 --> 00:03:29.800
For those of you that
don't have a copy,

00:03:29.800 --> 00:03:31.892
the book is called
"Stuffication."

00:03:31.892 --> 00:03:33.350
And what I'd like
to do is give you

00:03:33.350 --> 00:03:36.900
an introduction to that,
where it came from for me.

00:03:36.900 --> 00:03:42.280
And the best place, I think, to
begin a story of "Stuffication"

00:03:42.280 --> 00:03:45.500
in a talk like this,
is a place where

00:03:45.500 --> 00:03:48.550
I think a lot of
great stories begin.

00:03:48.550 --> 00:03:52.450
In a time of war with
the young couple in love.

00:03:52.450 --> 00:03:58.560
So about 70 years ago--
on January 27, 1940--

00:03:58.560 --> 00:04:01.690
war was raging in
some parts of Europe.

00:04:01.690 --> 00:04:03.509
But in London, it
was still quite.

00:04:03.509 --> 00:04:04.800
It was a quiet night in London.

00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:07.760
There was snow falling gently.

00:04:07.760 --> 00:04:12.280
And just out of a busy,
bustling, noisy dance

00:04:12.280 --> 00:04:15.365
hall, a man by the
name of Jack, wearing

00:04:15.365 --> 00:04:19.440
a dark suit, a white
shirt, and a Dickey bow tie

00:04:19.440 --> 00:04:23.580
stepped outside with
his new bride, Pam.

00:04:23.580 --> 00:04:27.190
And he turned to Pam, and
he said to her, "Come on.

00:04:27.190 --> 00:04:28.580
Let's go home."

00:04:28.580 --> 00:04:32.650
And they tramped through
snow to their first home.

00:04:32.650 --> 00:04:34.280
They had two rooms.

00:04:34.280 --> 00:04:36.830
They had a living room
and they had a bedroom.

00:04:36.830 --> 00:04:39.830
The kitchen and the
bathroom was shared

00:04:39.830 --> 00:04:41.830
with the other people who
lived in the building.

00:04:41.830 --> 00:04:44.250
A few years later,
they had a son, Allen.

00:04:44.250 --> 00:04:47.990
And when Allen grew too big to
share the bedroom with them,

00:04:47.990 --> 00:04:49.800
they gave him the bedroom.

00:04:49.800 --> 00:04:52.670
So every night, after
Allen had gone to bed,

00:04:52.670 --> 00:04:55.350
they would make up one
of those camp beds.

00:04:55.350 --> 00:04:56.392
You know those camp beds?

00:04:56.392 --> 00:04:58.433
They would make up a camp
bed in the living room,

00:04:58.433 --> 00:04:59.560
and they would sleep there.

00:04:59.560 --> 00:05:03.240
And every morning, before
Allen left for his paper route,

00:05:03.240 --> 00:05:06.980
he would wake to the
sound of sizzling

00:05:06.980 --> 00:05:10.300
and the smell of bacon,
and eggs, and sausages,

00:05:10.300 --> 00:05:12.470
and something that
English people used

00:05:12.470 --> 00:05:14.910
to eat called fried bread.

00:05:14.910 --> 00:05:17.350
And Jack would get up
every morning, early,

00:05:17.350 --> 00:05:18.670
and make that for Allen.

00:05:18.670 --> 00:05:21.100
And he did that every
day until the day Allen

00:05:21.100 --> 00:05:27.240
left for university-- for
Liverpool University-- in 1962.

00:05:27.240 --> 00:05:29.250
Allen was the first
person in his family

00:05:29.250 --> 00:05:31.752
ever to go to university.

00:05:31.752 --> 00:05:32.710
He made the most of it.

00:05:32.710 --> 00:05:36.690
He played for the
university soccer team.

00:05:36.690 --> 00:05:39.350
Notice I said soccer.

00:05:39.350 --> 00:05:42.630
He saw bands that
were hugely famous,

00:05:42.630 --> 00:05:44.360
but he saw them before
they were famous.

00:05:44.360 --> 00:05:47.134
So of course, he saw the
Beatles and the Rolling Stones.

00:05:47.134 --> 00:05:48.800
And if you ever meet
him, he'll tell you

00:05:48.800 --> 00:05:52.320
that within five
minutes of meeting him.

00:05:52.320 --> 00:05:55.460
And then he did what most
of us do after university.

00:05:55.460 --> 00:05:59.820
He settled down, he got a job,
he got married, he had kids,

00:05:59.820 --> 00:06:01.690
and I'm one of them.

00:06:01.690 --> 00:06:03.460
Allen is my father.

00:06:03.460 --> 00:06:06.210
Jack is my grandfather.

00:06:06.210 --> 00:06:09.090
This is my back story.

00:06:09.090 --> 00:06:12.520
Why am I telling you this?

00:06:12.520 --> 00:06:20.260
Because in the story of our
everyday, workaday family,

00:06:20.260 --> 00:06:22.800
you can see the story
of stuffication.

00:06:22.800 --> 00:06:24.990
In the story of our
very typical family,

00:06:24.990 --> 00:06:29.200
you can see the shift
in circumstances

00:06:29.200 --> 00:06:31.800
from scarcity to abundance.

00:06:31.800 --> 00:06:33.680
And you can see the
change, as well,

00:06:33.680 --> 00:06:37.670
in terms of what that means for
our attitudes, our aspirations,

00:06:37.670 --> 00:06:39.130
and our values.

00:06:39.130 --> 00:06:44.050
You see my grandparents, Jack
and Pam, they were typical.

00:06:44.050 --> 00:06:48.210
They lived not so very
far from survival mode

00:06:48.210 --> 00:06:50.510
as most people did back then.

00:06:50.510 --> 00:06:56.250
And as 99% of humans had always
done since the dawn of time.

00:06:56.250 --> 00:06:58.690
And my father was typical, too.

00:06:58.690 --> 00:07:02.820
He was a typical,
materialistic baby boomer.

00:07:02.820 --> 00:07:06.676
And as a typical,
materialistic baby boomer--

00:07:06.676 --> 00:07:09.830
one of the key things he did was
that-- he measured his life--

00:07:09.830 --> 00:07:11.780
in many ways-- in
material terms.

00:07:11.780 --> 00:07:14.970
Like the homes he lived
in and the cars he drove.

00:07:14.970 --> 00:07:16.320
And I remember them all.

00:07:16.320 --> 00:07:23.390
From in the '70s, kind of
boxy, sky blue Triumph Toledo.

00:07:23.390 --> 00:07:25.450
Anyone know what a
Triumph Toledo is?

00:07:25.450 --> 00:07:26.550
But you can picture it.

00:07:26.550 --> 00:07:28.130
British built.

00:07:28.130 --> 00:07:28.920
It was OK.

00:07:28.920 --> 00:07:31.760
And in the '80s, he
moved on to much slicker,

00:07:31.760 --> 00:07:35.500
sportier, kind of curvier,
more imported cars.

00:07:35.500 --> 00:07:39.070
And he ended the decade
in a red Porsche 911.

00:07:39.070 --> 00:07:42.210
And he was typical,
too-- I think

00:07:42.210 --> 00:07:44.890
for his time-- in
that he grew up

00:07:44.890 --> 00:07:48.230
believing in the
counterintuitive idea,

00:07:48.230 --> 00:07:51.330
we should gain ground in the
early 20th century, which

00:07:51.330 --> 00:07:53.870
was at the very
heart of materialism.

00:07:53.870 --> 00:07:56.844
And was sometimes called
the American paradox.

00:07:56.844 --> 00:07:57.760
And that was the idea.

00:07:57.760 --> 00:08:02.010
That if we wanted to have
more, we had to spend more.

00:08:02.010 --> 00:08:06.060
A virtuous circle of materialism
that changed circumstances.

00:08:06.060 --> 00:08:08.300
Now do you remember
the last time

00:08:08.300 --> 00:08:12.270
you called someone
materialistic?

00:08:12.270 --> 00:08:15.460
Have you done that
in the last month?

00:08:15.460 --> 00:08:17.720
I ask people this, and
most people say nothing.

00:08:17.720 --> 00:08:18.990
Then, this one.

00:08:18.990 --> 00:08:21.420
Have you thought
someone's materialistic

00:08:21.420 --> 00:08:23.560
in the last month?

00:08:23.560 --> 00:08:24.200
OK.

00:08:24.200 --> 00:08:26.620
And it's quite an insulting
thing to think isn't it right?

00:08:26.620 --> 00:08:28.910
You're kind of
putting someone down.

00:08:28.910 --> 00:08:30.400
And that makes sense today.

00:08:30.400 --> 00:08:33.289
But back then,
saying someone was

00:08:33.289 --> 00:08:38.169
materialistic-- materialism--
wasn't such a bad idea.

00:08:38.169 --> 00:08:41.169
In fact, it made perfect
sense because it offered

00:08:41.169 --> 00:08:44.390
my father, Alan, and the
rest of the baby boomers

00:08:44.390 --> 00:08:47.140
the straightest route--
the straightest road--

00:08:47.140 --> 00:08:51.670
from the scarcity they'd been
born into to the abundance

00:08:51.670 --> 00:08:53.824
that they were
helping to create.

00:08:53.824 --> 00:08:55.240
The abundance and
the better world

00:08:55.240 --> 00:08:58.470
they were making for
themselves, for the society

00:08:58.470 --> 00:09:02.600
around them, and
for their children.

00:09:02.600 --> 00:09:08.320
So I grew up the benefactor
of that to a large extent.

00:09:08.320 --> 00:09:12.260
And I also grew up
believing in that idea.

00:09:12.260 --> 00:09:14.750
And I grew up thinking I
would be just like my dad.

00:09:14.750 --> 00:09:16.520
I would be materialistic.

00:09:16.520 --> 00:09:18.960
But then something happened.

00:09:18.960 --> 00:09:20.930
And I think lots of
things have happened.

00:09:20.930 --> 00:09:26.290
And they've all added up to this
situation I call stuffication

00:09:26.290 --> 00:09:28.910
So stuffication is
that feeling you

00:09:28.910 --> 00:09:35.120
get when you open up the closet,
and it's full of clothes,

00:09:35.120 --> 00:09:37.840
but you can't find a
single thing to wear.

00:09:37.840 --> 00:09:40.990
It's that feeling you
get when you root around

00:09:40.990 --> 00:09:44.540
inside a cupboard-- whatever
it might be-- to find the one

00:09:44.540 --> 00:09:48.829
thing you need through a pile
of stuff that you don't use.

00:09:48.829 --> 00:09:50.370
Instead of thinking
of more-- the way

00:09:50.370 --> 00:09:52.850
we used to-- as a
good thing, we now

00:09:52.850 --> 00:09:56.450
think more means more
hassle, more to store,

00:09:56.450 --> 00:09:59.000
more to manage,
more to think about.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:01.890
More isn't better
anymore, it's worse.

00:10:01.890 --> 00:10:04.740
I think overwhelmed,
suffocating from stuff,

00:10:04.740 --> 00:10:07.770
we're feeling stuffication.

00:10:07.770 --> 00:10:11.660
Why isn't materialism
working anymore?

00:10:11.660 --> 00:10:14.840
Now, as with anything
as-- I think--

00:10:14.840 --> 00:10:17.609
seismic of stuffication, there
are loads of different answers.

00:10:17.609 --> 00:10:19.150
If you ask a different
expert, you'll

00:10:19.150 --> 00:10:21.180
get a different emphasis.

00:10:21.180 --> 00:10:25.010
So a philosopher might say that
it's to do with status anxiety.

00:10:25.010 --> 00:10:26.780
We've had enough
of stuff because we

00:10:26.780 --> 00:10:29.240
had enough of the
status anxiety that

00:10:29.240 --> 00:10:31.730
comes with materialistic
consumerism.

00:10:31.730 --> 00:10:35.070
A psychologist like Oliver
James might say it's affluenza.

00:10:35.070 --> 00:10:38.390
We've had enough of
stuff because it's

00:10:38.390 --> 00:10:39.930
giving us affluenza.

00:10:39.930 --> 00:10:43.950
Mass consumption is
leading to mass depression.

00:10:43.950 --> 00:10:47.830
And a political
scientist, might say it's

00:10:47.830 --> 00:10:49.830
because of the stable society.

00:10:49.830 --> 00:10:51.880
We're just not so
bothered about stuff

00:10:51.880 --> 00:10:53.940
anymore because
we know that we're

00:10:53.940 --> 00:10:56.090
going to have a roof
over our heads tonight,

00:10:56.090 --> 00:10:58.650
and there's going to be
food on the table tomorrow.

00:10:58.650 --> 00:11:02.670
We're just not so bothered
about the basic materialistic

00:11:02.670 --> 00:11:03.520
concerns anymore.

00:11:03.520 --> 00:11:07.870
We've climbed that first stage
of Maslow's hierarchy of needs.

00:11:07.870 --> 00:11:10.010
An anthropologist
might say-- I'm

00:11:10.010 --> 00:11:12.400
going to quote here
from the Center

00:11:12.400 --> 00:11:15.150
on the Everyday Lives of people,
based in Los Angeles, which

00:11:15.150 --> 00:11:18.610
has just completed the most
comprehensive report ever

00:11:18.610 --> 00:11:22.300
conducted into how
people are living today.

00:11:22.300 --> 00:11:28.450
And they said-- that
we have more material

00:11:28.450 --> 00:11:30.080
things than any
preceding society.

00:11:30.080 --> 00:11:33.560
They use the term "light-years
more possessions than any

00:11:33.560 --> 00:11:35.990
preceding society
in human history."

00:11:35.990 --> 00:11:39.950
That we're struggling
under material saturation,

00:11:39.950 --> 00:11:42.240
there we're coping with
extraordinary clutter,

00:11:42.240 --> 00:11:45.400
and that we're in the
middle of a clutter crisis.

00:11:45.400 --> 00:11:48.094
And a technologist
might-- I think-- smile

00:11:48.094 --> 00:11:49.010
at all of these ideas.

00:11:49.010 --> 00:11:53.650
Ya sure, status anxiety,
affluenza, the stable society,

00:11:53.650 --> 00:11:54.450
clutter crisis.

00:11:54.450 --> 00:11:57.170
This is all relevant as to
why we've had enough of stuff.

00:11:57.170 --> 00:12:01.120
But the real reason that we're
moving on from material things

00:12:01.120 --> 00:12:03.620
is because we can.

00:12:03.620 --> 00:12:07.580
Why have a room full of
Encyclopedia Britannicas when

00:12:07.580 --> 00:12:09.080
you can search for
the answer you're

00:12:09.080 --> 00:12:12.600
looking for through-- as
a search angle-- Google,

00:12:12.600 --> 00:12:14.310
you can use.

00:12:14.310 --> 00:12:17.430
Worth a try, that joke, right?

00:12:17.430 --> 00:12:19.260
That's why I'm a
writer, not a comedian.

00:12:19.260 --> 00:12:21.660
Anyway, but thanks.

00:12:21.660 --> 00:12:24.306
But why have a car, why
have a second car, when

00:12:24.306 --> 00:12:27.000
you can use Zipcar
or you can use Uber?

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:29.070
Why have a suitcase
full of books

00:12:29.070 --> 00:12:30.820
when you go on holiday--
for those of you

00:12:30.820 --> 00:12:32.702
that went on holiday
in the '70s and '80s--

00:12:32.702 --> 00:12:34.160
it was a real
challenge about which

00:12:34.160 --> 00:12:35.743
books were you going
to take with you.

00:12:35.743 --> 00:12:40.309
But why do that when
you have a Kindle?

00:12:40.309 --> 00:12:42.350
I think you know what it
looks like anyway right?

00:12:42.350 --> 00:12:45.540
But that-- thousands of books--
why have a room full of books?

00:12:48.840 --> 00:12:50.710
I think all of these
reasons is partly

00:12:50.710 --> 00:12:53.029
responsible for stuffication.

00:12:53.029 --> 00:12:54.570
But if you think
about them-- I think

00:12:54.570 --> 00:12:58.240
what's really interesting about
them is none of them are blips.

00:12:58.240 --> 00:12:59.740
None of them are
blips that are here

00:12:59.740 --> 00:13:02.620
one year and likely
to be gone the next.

00:13:02.620 --> 00:13:07.100
I think they're all observable,
observed, long-term trends.

00:13:07.100 --> 00:13:09.480
And that's why I
think stuffication

00:13:09.480 --> 00:13:14.520
is going to be the defining
problem of the 21st century.

00:13:14.520 --> 00:13:19.530
So how do you solve a
problem like stuffication?

00:13:19.530 --> 00:13:22.780
Now my job-- the job of a
trend forecaster, not comedian

00:13:22.780 --> 00:13:27.540
as we've already
established-- is fascinating.

00:13:27.540 --> 00:13:31.320
It gives me really
interesting insight,

00:13:31.320 --> 00:13:33.510
gives me a really
unique viewpoint,

00:13:33.510 --> 00:13:37.510
and it opens me up
to a lot of ridicule.

00:13:37.510 --> 00:13:40.790
As Yogi Berra said, "It's
hard to make predictions,

00:13:40.790 --> 00:13:42.969
particularly about the future.

00:13:42.969 --> 00:13:45.260
And the thing is, if you're
going to make a prediction,

00:13:45.260 --> 00:13:46.050
if you're going
to say something's

00:13:46.050 --> 00:13:48.560
going to happen in the
future, at the very least,

00:13:48.560 --> 00:13:51.110
you'd better have a
decent methodology.

00:13:51.110 --> 00:13:56.980
So I don't look
into a crystal ball.

00:13:56.980 --> 00:14:00.050
And I don't read tea
leaves, and I've tried.

00:14:00.050 --> 00:14:02.700
Maybe in Rishikesh.

00:14:02.700 --> 00:14:07.950
And I don't breath in vapors
by the Oracle at Delphi.

00:14:07.950 --> 00:14:10.420
The method I use is
far less ancient,

00:14:10.420 --> 00:14:13.760
but I think it's
far more robust.

00:14:13.760 --> 00:14:16.000
It's inspired by
something a futurist--

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:18.360
called William
Gibson-- once said,

00:14:18.360 --> 00:14:20.400
that "The future
is already here,

00:14:20.400 --> 00:14:23.020
it's just not very
evenly distributed. "

00:14:23.020 --> 00:14:26.460
And it's informed by a way
of reading cultural change,

00:14:26.460 --> 00:14:31.410
which has been applied more than
5,000 times since it was first

00:14:31.410 --> 00:14:34.870
codified by a sociologist
called Everett Rogers,

00:14:34.870 --> 00:14:38.064
Iowa State University in 1962.

00:14:38.064 --> 00:14:39.480
Some of you will
have heard of it.

00:14:39.480 --> 00:14:41.460
It's the diffusion
of innovations.

00:14:41.460 --> 00:14:44.290
And it's a way of reading
cultural change that works out

00:14:44.290 --> 00:14:48.270
how ideas, innovations,
new ways of living,

00:14:48.270 --> 00:14:50.430
working, cooking,
whatever it might be,

00:14:50.430 --> 00:14:53.326
spread from the innovators--
the few innovators

00:14:53.326 --> 00:14:57.530
to the early adopters, the
early majority, late majority,

00:14:57.530 --> 00:14:58.970
and [INAUDIBLE].

00:14:58.970 --> 00:15:05.200
So my job is to spot the
future here in the present.

00:15:05.200 --> 00:15:09.060
It's to identify the
innovators in the innovations,

00:15:09.060 --> 00:15:12.170
the big ideas that are
going to catch on and spread

00:15:12.170 --> 00:15:18.340
from these few people to
the many in the mainstream.

00:15:18.340 --> 00:15:22.220
So I've looked all around the
world looking for the answer,

00:15:22.220 --> 00:15:25.480
looking to understand
this problem better

00:15:25.480 --> 00:15:29.340
and to find an idea-- which
I think-- has the power,

00:15:29.340 --> 00:15:33.860
has the legs, has the ability
to move from these few

00:15:33.860 --> 00:15:35.210
to these many.

00:15:35.210 --> 00:15:38.180
And as you can imagine, I've
run up many blind alleys.

00:15:38.180 --> 00:15:40.470
I've kind of come
to lots of dead ends

00:15:40.470 --> 00:15:44.730
and all kinds of things that
I thought were the answer.

00:15:44.730 --> 00:15:47.620
Minimalism is a great example.

00:15:47.620 --> 00:15:49.392
But of all the things
I've looked at--

00:15:49.392 --> 00:15:50.850
and the book is,
to a large extent,

00:15:50.850 --> 00:15:53.616
a kind of process of me
going through this one,

00:15:53.616 --> 00:15:54.240
does this work?

00:15:54.240 --> 00:15:58.290
This one, does it work?-- I've
come across one idea, which

00:15:58.290 --> 00:16:01.640
I think is going to catch
on and become dominant.

00:16:01.640 --> 00:16:03.030
I call it experientialism.

00:16:03.030 --> 00:16:08.040
And the people who live
this way, experientialists.

00:16:08.040 --> 00:16:12.880
So the experientialists,
instead of looking for status,

00:16:12.880 --> 00:16:17.120
identity, happiness, and
meaning in material things--

00:16:17.120 --> 00:16:19.490
like materialists
did-- experientialists

00:16:19.490 --> 00:16:23.130
are finding status,
identity, happiness,

00:16:23.130 --> 00:16:27.020
and meaning, and
experiences instead.

00:16:27.020 --> 00:16:32.220
Experientialism-- and I've
said it a lot of times--

00:16:32.220 --> 00:16:37.240
I think can solve a
problem like stuffication.

00:16:37.240 --> 00:16:39.830
More importantly,
experientialism, I believe,

00:16:39.830 --> 00:16:42.510
will solve stuffication.

00:16:42.510 --> 00:16:46.580
And I say that because
firstly, it's better.

00:16:46.580 --> 00:16:48.680
It's just better
the materialism.

00:16:48.680 --> 00:16:51.130
Giving us status,
giving us identity,

00:16:51.130 --> 00:16:55.305
giving us meaning in our
lives, and making us happy.

00:16:55.305 --> 00:16:57.180
But more important than
that-- more important

00:16:57.180 --> 00:17:00.042
than being better--
I've seen the signs.

00:17:00.042 --> 00:17:01.000
I've seen the evidence.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:06.180
Even if it's still
unevenly distributed,

00:17:06.180 --> 00:17:09.369
that we are moving
away from materialism,

00:17:09.369 --> 00:17:12.150
and the experientialism
is making the leap

00:17:12.150 --> 00:17:17.250
from the innovative few to
the many in the mainstream.

00:17:17.250 --> 00:17:19.364
So first up,
there's the evidence

00:17:19.364 --> 00:17:21.680
that shows that our
attitudes are changing.

00:17:21.680 --> 00:17:23.520
There's a guy called
Ron Inglehart-- he's

00:17:23.520 --> 00:17:26.849
a political scientist at
the University of Michigan--

00:17:26.849 --> 00:17:32.110
and based on a hunch that
Ron had back in 1969,

00:17:32.110 --> 00:17:33.610
he started studying
our attitudes.

00:17:33.610 --> 00:17:37.710
And in 1970, he found
that 80% of people

00:17:37.710 --> 00:17:40.840
were materialistic
in Western countries.

00:17:40.840 --> 00:17:44.680
Now-- in today's
world-- it's 50%.

00:17:44.680 --> 00:17:47.830
So you can see very clear,
there is long-term decline

00:17:47.830 --> 00:17:51.330
in how materialistic we are.

00:17:51.330 --> 00:17:53.750
And I think where it's really
interesting is that, as well

00:17:53.750 --> 00:17:56.300
as our attitudes changing,
there is now evidence

00:17:56.300 --> 00:17:59.420
that our behavior is
changing, as well.

00:17:59.420 --> 00:18:01.850
There's a guy called Chris
Goodall-- he's a Cambridge

00:18:01.850 --> 00:18:04.070
grad, he was a
McKinsey consultant,

00:18:04.070 --> 00:18:07.890
he taught economics at
Harvard for a time--

00:18:07.890 --> 00:18:12.340
he has analyzed the material
flows-- the flow of materials--

00:18:12.340 --> 00:18:15.040
through Western
economies, so looking

00:18:15.040 --> 00:18:17.140
at the States and
the UK, for example.

00:18:17.140 --> 00:18:21.100
And he's discovered that we
are consuming less stuff.

00:18:21.100 --> 00:18:25.140
Less paper, concrete,
cars, steel, fertilizers,

00:18:25.140 --> 00:18:27.540
electricity.

00:18:27.540 --> 00:18:31.430
He's happy having
seen all this evidence

00:18:31.430 --> 00:18:35.020
to conclude that we've reached
the point of peak stuff,

00:18:35.020 --> 00:18:37.680
and that we're now
passing that point.

00:18:37.680 --> 00:18:40.800
Now besides those
there's technology.

00:18:40.800 --> 00:18:44.580
And I mean, technology in
terms of wearable tech.

00:18:44.580 --> 00:18:48.150
For example, the quantified
self movement, life logging,

00:18:48.150 --> 00:18:49.880
and social media.

00:18:49.880 --> 00:18:52.140
All of these things
make our lives

00:18:52.140 --> 00:18:56.180
much more connected, much
more trackable, and much more

00:18:56.180 --> 00:18:57.660
sharable.

00:18:57.660 --> 00:19:01.380
I imagine you're
aware of this, right?

00:19:01.380 --> 00:19:06.260
What's really interesting for me
about all these technologies--

00:19:06.260 --> 00:19:08.380
in particular, I think
the social aspect of it,

00:19:08.380 --> 00:19:10.420
social media-- is
they're fundamentally

00:19:10.420 --> 00:19:15.420
changing how we express our
identities and we get status.

00:19:15.420 --> 00:19:17.150
So go back to the 20th century.

00:19:17.150 --> 00:19:19.900
The best way to get status
and express your identity

00:19:19.900 --> 00:19:22.510
in the 20th century,
was through the stuff

00:19:22.510 --> 00:19:25.260
you owned-- handbag,
car, shoes, whatever

00:19:25.260 --> 00:19:27.930
it might be-- not
from what you did.

00:19:27.930 --> 00:19:31.520
Because back then,
who knew that you'd

00:19:31.520 --> 00:19:37.930
been to Utah or Tahoe
skiing for the weekend?

00:19:37.930 --> 00:19:41.890
Who knew you'd been to
Marrakech on your vacation?

00:19:41.890 --> 00:19:44.380
Who knew you'd been to a
really great talk from a trend

00:19:44.380 --> 00:19:47.071
forecaster at lunch time?

00:19:47.071 --> 00:19:48.570
Thank you for staying
with me there.

00:19:48.570 --> 00:19:51.260
I appreciate that.

00:19:51.260 --> 00:19:54.692
My wife says that was a
funny joke, but they you go.

00:19:54.692 --> 00:19:56.150
But the thing is,
in today's world,

00:19:56.150 --> 00:19:59.810
with all your followers on
Twitter, Instagram, Google+,

00:19:59.810 --> 00:20:05.140
and Facebook-- your friends,
fans, followers-- they do.

00:20:05.140 --> 00:20:08.350
So now if you take a
picture from the chair

00:20:08.350 --> 00:20:11.300
lift in Squaw
Valley or Park City,

00:20:11.300 --> 00:20:14.250
or if you take a picture of the
sun setting behind the Atlas

00:20:14.250 --> 00:20:18.260
mountains from the rooftop
of your riad in Marrakech,

00:20:18.260 --> 00:20:20.400
or you even tweet a
quote from something

00:20:20.400 --> 00:20:23.810
you heard a talk at lunch time.

00:20:23.810 --> 00:20:24.585
And this matters.

00:20:24.585 --> 00:20:26.210
This matters because
it matters for how

00:20:26.210 --> 00:20:28.840
we express our identities
and we get our status.

00:20:28.840 --> 00:20:32.310
And that matters for people
because status and identity

00:20:32.310 --> 00:20:33.730
matters, right?

00:20:33.730 --> 00:20:35.430
And social media
and this technology

00:20:35.430 --> 00:20:38.630
matters for the rise
of experientialism

00:20:38.630 --> 00:20:42.400
because this isn't the
innovative few anymore.

00:20:42.400 --> 00:20:46.290
There are hundreds of millions
of people using Instagram,

00:20:46.290 --> 00:20:47.250
Twitter, and Google+.

00:20:47.250 --> 00:20:50.210
There's 1.2 billion
people on Facebook--

00:20:50.210 --> 00:20:54.780
that's as many people as are
in the Catholic Church-- who

00:20:54.780 --> 00:20:59.440
are expressing their identities
and getting their status,

00:20:59.440 --> 00:21:03.120
not from what they have,
but from what they do.

00:21:03.120 --> 00:21:06.400
And this matters-- I
believe-- for you, for me,

00:21:06.400 --> 00:21:07.810
and for all of us.

00:21:07.810 --> 00:21:11.060
The question is, I guess, how?

00:21:11.060 --> 00:21:16.420
About 12 years ago--
on January 27, 2002--

00:21:16.420 --> 00:21:18.450
my father brought
my grandparents--

00:21:18.450 --> 00:21:23.030
Jack and Pam-- over for
lunch to my new apartment.

00:21:23.030 --> 00:21:24.270
It was my first home.

00:21:24.270 --> 00:21:26.280
It was in Brixton,
in south London

00:21:26.280 --> 00:21:29.020
and it had three bedrooms.

00:21:29.020 --> 00:21:31.610
I had a living room, I had
a separate dining room,

00:21:31.610 --> 00:21:35.390
a separate kitchen, had this
great, big, west facing garden.

00:21:35.390 --> 00:21:37.740
It was awesome for parties.

00:21:37.740 --> 00:21:39.020
It was a great first home.

00:21:39.020 --> 00:21:40.228
And they come over for lunch.

00:21:40.228 --> 00:21:43.050
And I had a job in
advertising at the time.

00:21:43.050 --> 00:21:44.750
I think I was a bit
gung-ho, talking

00:21:44.750 --> 00:21:48.110
quite big about how successful
I was and was going to be.

00:21:48.110 --> 00:21:51.370
And just before they
left, my grandfather

00:21:51.370 --> 00:21:53.840
handed me an envelope.

00:21:53.840 --> 00:21:58.030
And just after they left, I
opened it, as you can imagine.

00:21:58.030 --> 00:21:59.470
And it had a note in it.

00:21:59.470 --> 00:22:04.580
And it had on it 27/1/2002-- he
wrote the date the British way

00:22:04.580 --> 00:22:11.096
with the day and then the
month-- "On this day in 1940,

00:22:11.096 --> 00:22:14.820
Nana and I tramped through
snow to our first home.

00:22:14.820 --> 00:22:17.850
Memories live
longer than dreams.

00:22:17.850 --> 00:22:20.010
Good luck."

00:22:20.010 --> 00:22:24.380
A little bit later-- probably 20
to 25 minutes later-- my father

00:22:24.380 --> 00:22:28.460
was just driving back starting
to cross the river Thames--

00:22:28.460 --> 00:22:30.690
it was a black 5 Series
BMW, if you're keep up

00:22:30.690 --> 00:22:36.759
with the cars of my father--
and my grandfather choked.

00:22:36.759 --> 00:22:38.300
And he kind of
collapsed in his seat.

00:22:38.300 --> 00:22:39.930
My father obviously stopped.

00:22:39.930 --> 00:22:43.760
And then he drove
as fast as he could.

00:22:43.760 --> 00:22:44.930
He jumped lights.

00:22:44.930 --> 00:22:47.360
He actually got pulled over
and got a police escort.

00:22:47.360 --> 00:22:49.360
He did everything he could
to get my grandfather

00:22:49.360 --> 00:22:51.530
to a hospital as
quickly as possible.

00:22:56.480 --> 00:22:59.680
He did what he could, but my
grandfather died that day.

00:22:59.680 --> 00:23:03.160
And obviously, I
thought about the note

00:23:03.160 --> 00:23:08.850
that he gave me quite
a lot since then.

00:23:08.850 --> 00:23:12.380
First of all, did
he know that he

00:23:12.380 --> 00:23:15.900
was going to die that day
when he gave me that note?

00:23:15.900 --> 00:23:21.000
And what did he mean by memories
live longer than dreams?

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:27.130
Did he mean that the past is
not as good as the future?

00:23:27.130 --> 00:23:32.320
Or did he mean-- as I've come
to believe-- that the material

00:23:32.320 --> 00:23:35.400
dreams are all well
and good, but life

00:23:35.400 --> 00:23:40.580
is made of up memories,
which come from experiences?

00:23:40.580 --> 00:23:45.140
Now whatever he meant, it
was quite a passing shot.

00:23:45.140 --> 00:23:50.000
In those final
moments, to address

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:52.310
the most important
question a person can ask.

00:23:52.310 --> 00:23:55.910
The question that Aristotle
asked in the Nicomachean

00:23:55.910 --> 00:23:57.870
Ethics, almost 2 and
1/2 thousand years ago.

00:23:57.870 --> 00:24:02.370
The question every one of us
should ask-- as individuals,

00:24:02.370 --> 00:24:05.750
as parents, as
influential people

00:24:05.750 --> 00:24:09.960
who market stuff and change the
world, being citizens or where

00:24:09.960 --> 00:24:11.720
we work, whatever it might be.

00:24:11.720 --> 00:24:16.320
And the question is-- I think
you know the question, right?

00:24:16.320 --> 00:24:20.570
How should we live
in order to be happy?

00:24:20.570 --> 00:24:23.320
And in the 20th century,
I think the answer

00:24:23.320 --> 00:24:26.510
to that, in many
ways, was clear.

00:24:26.510 --> 00:24:29.080
You should be
materialistic because that

00:24:29.080 --> 00:24:32.570
was creating abundance
for everybody.

00:24:32.570 --> 00:24:36.680
And I think in the 21st
century, when our problem isn't

00:24:36.680 --> 00:24:40.780
scarcity, our problem is
abundance-- I think so much

00:24:40.780 --> 00:24:43.560
abundance that there's time
of stuffication-- I think

00:24:43.560 --> 00:24:45.890
that quite the answer has
fundamentally changed.

00:24:48.570 --> 00:24:53.120
So the story of
stuffication ends with you.

00:24:56.470 --> 00:25:00.480
What are you going to do about
the most pressing problem

00:25:00.480 --> 00:25:03.520
of our time?

00:25:03.520 --> 00:25:09.100
There are 3 things you can do
to try out experientialism.

00:25:09.100 --> 00:25:09.900
Three steps.

00:25:09.900 --> 00:25:12.630
First step, destufficate.

00:25:12.630 --> 00:25:15.954
Step two, don't restufficate.

00:25:15.954 --> 00:25:17.870
Once you've gone through
the bother of getting

00:25:17.870 --> 00:25:20.078
rid of all that stuff you
don't wear, you don't need,

00:25:20.078 --> 00:25:21.740
you don't use.

00:25:21.740 --> 00:25:23.620
And it's so easy to
go out when you've

00:25:23.620 --> 00:25:25.930
created space in your
closet on your shelf,

00:25:25.930 --> 00:25:28.810
because we've been trained
to be consumers, to do that.

00:25:28.810 --> 00:25:31.700
But it's really important
not to go out and buy

00:25:31.700 --> 00:25:35.530
more stuff you don't need,
you don't use, you don't wear.

00:25:35.530 --> 00:25:38.192
But for me, step
3 is the best bet.

00:25:38.192 --> 00:25:39.900
Because 1 and 2 are
just hygiene factors.

00:25:39.900 --> 00:25:41.108
They're just starting points.

00:25:41.108 --> 00:25:43.300
Step 3 is a game.

00:25:43.300 --> 00:25:46.450
And it's a game I like to think
of as the Brewster's Millions

00:25:46.450 --> 00:25:48.260
game.

00:25:48.260 --> 00:25:51.170
Some of you probably won't
have read the 1902 novel

00:25:51.170 --> 00:25:54.060
or seen the 1985 movie.

00:25:54.060 --> 00:25:57.030
Anyone got no idea what
Brewsters Millions is?

00:25:57.030 --> 00:25:57.582
All right.

00:25:57.582 --> 00:25:58.290
Oh, a few of you.

00:25:58.290 --> 00:25:59.610
OK.

00:25:59.610 --> 00:26:05.226
It only got 6.4 out of 10 on
IMDB, which is a crying shame

00:26:05.226 --> 00:26:05.850
and it's wrong.

00:26:05.850 --> 00:26:06.780
It's a great movie.

00:26:06.780 --> 00:26:07.660
Anyway.

00:26:07.660 --> 00:26:09.980
So Brewster's
Millions, the movie,

00:26:09.980 --> 00:26:13.960
is about this guy who has to
spend $30 million in a month

00:26:13.960 --> 00:26:19.290
and have nothing physical,
tangible to show for it.

00:26:19.290 --> 00:26:21.870
Now to play the
game properly, you

00:26:21.870 --> 00:26:26.550
don't have to spend $30 million
in a month, unless you have it,

00:26:26.550 --> 00:26:29.670
that's obviously your choice.

00:26:29.670 --> 00:26:32.480
But what you do have to do--
to play the game properly

00:26:32.480 --> 00:26:34.370
and to really experience
the benefits-- is

00:26:34.370 --> 00:26:36.690
to spend the same
amount of money

00:26:36.690 --> 00:26:39.630
that you'd spend
in a normal month,

00:26:39.630 --> 00:26:42.200
but have nothing
physical, tangible

00:26:42.200 --> 00:26:44.620
to show for it at the end.

00:26:44.620 --> 00:26:48.140
And that's all you have to do
to join the experientialists.

00:26:50.650 --> 00:26:55.610
And if you do that-- I promise
you-- you'll have more stories,

00:26:55.610 --> 00:26:59.370
you'll have more status,
you'll be happier,

00:26:59.370 --> 00:27:03.400
life will feel like it
has a lot more meaning.

00:27:03.400 --> 00:27:06.460
But more than that, I think
you'll be one of the pioneers.

00:27:06.460 --> 00:27:08.770
I think you'll be one
of the pioneers leading

00:27:08.770 --> 00:27:12.670
the rest of society out of
the storm of stuffication

00:27:12.670 --> 00:27:16.020
on the straightest, most
positive, most aspirational,

00:27:16.020 --> 00:27:19.340
most fun route to
a better world.

00:27:19.340 --> 00:27:22.810
I think you'll be one
of the pioneers leading

00:27:22.810 --> 00:27:24.860
the rest of America,
the rest of the West,

00:27:24.860 --> 00:27:29.230
the rest of the world from
the old age of materialism

00:27:29.230 --> 00:27:33.340
to this new era of
experientialism.

00:27:33.340 --> 00:27:35.340
And more than that
even, I think you'll

00:27:35.340 --> 00:27:38.010
understand what my
grandfather, Jack, meant

00:27:38.010 --> 00:27:40.465
that memories live
longer than dreams.

00:27:43.890 --> 00:27:44.540
Thank you.

