that I took on my camcorder?

00:35:07.180 --> 00:35:08.430
JAMES WALLMAN: Great question.

00:35:08.430 --> 00:35:08.930
Thank you.

00:35:08.930 --> 00:35:12.670
I think this comes to the heart
why social media is important.

00:35:12.670 --> 00:35:16.599
If you-- I'm going to guess
you're in your 20s, right?

00:35:16.599 --> 00:35:17.640
AUDIENCE: Just left them.

00:35:17.640 --> 00:35:19.130
JAMES WALLMAN: OK.

00:35:19.130 --> 00:35:23.550
So if you went on holiday in
the '90s, or your friends--

00:35:23.550 --> 00:35:26.500
you ever remember going to a
friend's house in the '90s,

00:35:26.500 --> 00:35:28.572
and they-- would pull
out their holiday snaps.

00:35:28.572 --> 00:35:30.780
And there was that that
awful moment where you think,

00:35:30.780 --> 00:35:31.500
Oh, God.

00:35:31.500 --> 00:35:34.320
And they'd show you a
picture Jean at the Acropolis

00:35:34.320 --> 00:35:38.180
and then Jean eats souvlaki and
then Jean doing something else.

00:35:38.180 --> 00:35:41.480
How painfully dull
was that, right?

00:35:41.480 --> 00:35:43.230
And it took them-- if
you think about it--

00:35:43.230 --> 00:35:45.720
how long did it
take them to share

00:35:45.720 --> 00:35:47.685
their holiday with people?

00:35:47.685 --> 00:35:50.060
Because they would have had
to have, not just you around,

00:35:50.060 --> 00:35:51.250
all their other friends.

00:35:51.250 --> 00:35:54.235
So let's say it's
the '90s, and you

00:35:54.235 --> 00:35:56.140
go on a really
incredible holiday.

00:35:56.140 --> 00:35:57.802
Let's say you go to Greece, and
you're really excited about it,

00:35:57.802 --> 00:35:59.330
and you go see the
ruins, et cetera.

00:35:59.330 --> 00:36:01.750
And you want to tell
100 of your best friends

00:36:01.750 --> 00:36:03.560
about your holiday.

00:36:03.560 --> 00:36:06.137
And let's say-- it's hard
to do it at a party--

00:36:06.137 --> 00:36:08.470
so you need to see them at
dinner or at personal drinks,

00:36:08.470 --> 00:36:09.460
right?

00:36:09.460 --> 00:36:12.230
So let's say you can
manage 6 people at a time.

00:36:12.230 --> 00:36:13.810
Stay with me here for the math.

00:36:13.810 --> 00:36:17.520
So you've got to have 10,
15 different arrangements

00:36:17.520 --> 00:36:19.100
to see people.

00:36:19.100 --> 00:36:22.440
That takes a long time-- takes
like a couple of months--

00:36:22.440 --> 00:36:25.920
to share with people
your experiences.

00:36:25.920 --> 00:36:28.450
Whereas today, you could
post it on Facebook,

00:36:28.450 --> 00:36:30.460
and you've got your
500, 600 friends that

00:36:30.460 --> 00:36:32.130
are right there that can see it.

00:36:32.130 --> 00:36:36.540
So what social media has done
has catalyzed that opportunity

00:36:36.540 --> 00:36:38.362
to share what you're doing.

00:36:38.362 --> 00:36:39.820
So if you'd just
run a Tough Mudder

00:36:39.820 --> 00:36:42.690
course-- I think this is one of
the reasons why Tough Mudder is

00:36:42.690 --> 00:36:46.490
increasing so quickly--
you can instantly

00:36:46.490 --> 00:36:47.950
share that with people.

00:36:47.950 --> 00:36:51.510
And that has a real impact
on how you see yourself.

00:36:51.510 --> 00:36:56.050
It has a real impact on how you
present yourselves to others.

00:36:56.050 --> 00:36:59.820
So that's what social
media has done.

00:36:59.820 --> 00:37:01.900
I constantly hear
about Facebook,

00:37:01.900 --> 00:37:03.410
it'll be something else next.

00:37:03.410 --> 00:37:06.740
It doesn't matter which platform
it is that people are using.

00:37:06.740 --> 00:37:09.190
We now are used to the
idea of social media.

00:37:09.190 --> 00:37:11.102
It will stay with us.

00:37:11.102 --> 00:37:13.060
Now that means there's
been a fundamental shift

00:37:13.060 --> 00:37:15.690
from having things
to doing things

00:37:15.690 --> 00:37:17.820
in terms of expressing
our identities.

