00:37:49.350 --> 00:37:51.030
series on your education.

00:37:51.030 --> 00:37:54.850
And so it's not so much that
I like Instagraming photos

00:37:54.850 --> 00:37:58.190
from my bike ride more, as I
feel like I have actually less

00:37:58.190 --> 00:38:00.100
money to spend on stuff.

00:38:00.100 --> 00:38:04.050
And so I'm wondering what
the recession you feel

00:38:04.050 --> 00:38:07.387
might play into this movement
away from stuff, how you think

00:38:07.387 --> 00:38:09.970
it's maybe going to be different
for people for my generation,

00:38:09.970 --> 00:38:12.810
for whom, things are
just going to become

00:38:12.810 --> 00:38:14.740
less part of the picture
because of the rising

00:38:14.740 --> 00:38:17.720
cost of other things, like
healthcare, like education.

00:38:17.720 --> 00:38:19.590
And whether or
not you think then

00:38:19.590 --> 00:38:22.270
that some of your advice on how
you would implement those three

00:38:22.270 --> 00:38:25.510
steps would be different.

00:38:25.510 --> 00:38:27.050
JAMES WALLMAN: Good questions.

00:38:27.050 --> 00:38:28.450
I think you've asked me
quite a lot of things there.

00:38:28.450 --> 00:38:29.990
I'm going to try
to say back to you.

00:38:29.990 --> 00:38:30.430
No, it's fine.

00:38:30.430 --> 00:38:32.640
It's really interesting.
, Especially since you are

00:38:32.640 --> 00:38:34.610
a Millennial, it's very easy
for me stand here and say,

00:38:34.610 --> 00:38:37.030
Millennial's are doing this,
but you are a Millennial.

00:38:37.030 --> 00:38:41.050
So you're asking me,
how should a Millennial

00:38:41.050 --> 00:38:44.090
implement those three steps?

00:38:44.090 --> 00:38:49.900
That was your final part, but
before that you were saying,

00:38:49.900 --> 00:38:51.730
what do I think about education?

00:38:51.730 --> 00:38:53.990
Where does education
fit into this?

00:38:53.990 --> 00:38:54.657
And the economy.

00:38:54.657 --> 00:38:56.198
Education, economy,
and how does that

00:38:56.198 --> 00:38:58.315
affect Millennials and
this shift from materialism

00:38:58.315 --> 00:38:59.320
to experientialism.

00:38:59.320 --> 00:39:03.056
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I'm wondering
how you see the recession

00:39:03.056 --> 00:39:05.680
and rising costs of education is
factoring into people's choice

00:39:05.680 --> 00:39:07.309
not to buy things.

00:39:07.309 --> 00:39:08.350
JAMES WALLMAN: All right.

00:39:08.350 --> 00:39:12.580
So the economy is a
really complicated one--

00:39:12.580 --> 00:39:15.322
to be frank with you--
because it's certainly

00:39:15.322 --> 00:39:17.030
something I would
never try and forecast.

00:39:17.030 --> 00:39:18.590
Because there's so much.

00:39:21.722 --> 00:39:23.180
In terms of how it
affects people--

00:39:23.180 --> 00:39:25.940
I think is really
interesting because-- there's

00:39:25.940 --> 00:39:28.850
a particular time of your life
and if there is a recession--

00:39:28.850 --> 00:39:32.000
or there's a lack of money in
your family around that time--

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:34.060
you become much
more materialistic

00:39:34.060 --> 00:39:35.290
than other people.

00:39:35.290 --> 00:39:36.915
So this kind of
broad brush approach,

00:39:36.915 --> 00:39:39.290
that the boomers were this,
and the Millennials are this,

00:39:39.290 --> 00:39:43.100
and Gen X are like this,
it's quite broad brush

00:39:43.100 --> 00:39:44.560
over-- generalizations.

00:39:44.560 --> 00:39:45.850
And there will be different
people within that.

00:39:45.850 --> 00:39:47.470
My brother and I
are two years apart,

00:39:47.470 --> 00:39:49.680
and he is far more
materialistic than me.

00:39:49.680 --> 00:39:52.585
Because not long after my
father having that Porsche,

00:39:52.585 --> 00:39:53.662
his company disappeared.

00:39:53.662 --> 00:39:55.370
And therefore, all
the money did as well.

00:39:55.370 --> 00:39:57.810
Therefore, my brother went
through a crucial period

00:39:57.810 --> 00:39:59.340
where we had no money.

00:39:59.340 --> 00:40:01.740
And therefore, he's much
more materialistic than I am.

00:40:01.740 --> 00:40:04.789
So the economy will affect
this is an interesting way.

00:40:04.789 --> 00:40:06.330
And some people will
feel less stable

00:40:06.330 --> 00:40:09.600
and therefore, become
more materialistic.

00:40:09.600 --> 00:40:11.250
But we've also had
recessions before.

00:40:11.250 --> 00:40:13.045
That kind of comes and goes.

00:40:13.045 --> 00:40:14.420
I don't know if
you Nate Silver's

00:40:14.420 --> 00:40:17.570
"The Signal and the Noise" but
if you consider how forecasting

00:40:17.570 --> 00:40:19.990
works, and the way
that trends work,

00:40:19.990 --> 00:40:23.350
you may consider the idea
that 80% of people that

00:40:23.350 --> 00:40:25.410
were materialistic,
and now it's 50%.

00:40:25.410 --> 00:40:29.120
Within that time, it
will go down a bit.

00:40:29.120 --> 00:40:31.280
So I think there's
still a long term trend.

00:40:31.280 --> 00:40:32.810
In terms of
education, I would say

00:40:32.810 --> 00:40:36.700
education is a great example
of an experiential good.

00:40:36.700 --> 00:40:38.590
It's not tangible.

00:40:38.590 --> 00:40:41.010
I don't know what your
educational situation is,

00:40:41.010 --> 00:40:45.190
but for those of us that have
a degree of the first level,

00:40:45.190 --> 00:40:50.840
the next level, or a doctorate,
how many of us have the--

00:40:50.840 --> 00:40:52.710
do you get
certificates over here?

00:40:52.710 --> 00:40:53.990
Do you keep them?

00:40:53.990 --> 00:40:57.640
I have no idea where
my certificates are.

00:40:57.640 --> 00:41:00.390
I don't think my
mom has them even.

00:41:00.390 --> 00:41:02.800
It's very much an
experiential good.

00:41:02.800 --> 00:41:03.970
It's not a material good.

00:41:03.970 --> 00:41:06.860
It's not a kind of solid thing.

00:41:06.860 --> 00:41:10.770
And as a Millennial, in
terms of those three ideas,

00:41:10.770 --> 00:41:13.210
I don't actually think it
makes a difference what age

00:41:13.210 --> 00:41:15.050
or who you are.

00:41:15.050 --> 00:41:19.580
The simple aspect of it is,
if you want to be happier--

00:41:19.580 --> 00:41:20.926
And the research is fascinating.

00:41:20.926 --> 00:41:22.800
If you look at the
research that experiential

00:41:22.800 --> 00:41:23.716
versus material goods.

00:41:23.716 --> 00:41:25.690
There's one great example.

00:41:25.690 --> 00:41:29.740
People are happier, if they
talk about experiences.

00:41:29.740 --> 00:41:31.560
And we enjoy listening
to people that

00:41:31.560 --> 00:41:33.400
talk about experiences more.

00:41:33.400 --> 00:41:36.220
So on that basis, if
you've got a choice,

00:41:36.220 --> 00:41:38.050
you're feeling bored
on a Saturday morning,

00:41:38.050 --> 00:41:40.430
go spend your money and
time doing an experience.

00:41:40.430 --> 00:41:42.560
You'll be happier because
you'll be doing it.

00:41:42.560 --> 00:41:45.150
You'll be happier because when
you talk to people about it,

00:41:45.150 --> 00:41:46.219
you'll be happier.

00:41:46.219 --> 00:41:48.010
And you'll have more
friends because people

00:41:48.010 --> 00:41:49.810
will want to listen to you more.

00:41:49.810 --> 00:41:51.920
So an experiential good
is so much more positive.

00:41:51.920 --> 00:41:55.245
The other aspects about a
experiential good-- as opposed

00:41:55.245 --> 00:41:56.828
a material good--
have you ever bought

00:41:56.828 --> 00:41:59.790
a pair of shoes that squeak
when you walk in them?

00:41:59.790 --> 00:42:01.610
Or those trousers
that seem to swish?

00:42:01.610 --> 00:42:02.790
Or a coat.

00:42:02.790 --> 00:42:05.240
What do you do with those
shoes, or those things?

00:42:05.240 --> 00:42:06.880
You wear them but
they annoy you.

00:42:06.880 --> 00:42:08.060
You never want to wear them.

00:42:08.060 --> 00:42:11.090
Eventually, you throw them
away or do you just squeak?

00:42:11.090 --> 00:42:12.181
Maybe you do.

00:42:12.181 --> 00:42:14.680
The thing about a material good,
if you buy a material good,

00:42:14.680 --> 00:42:17.180
and it's not very good, there's
nothing you can do about it.

00:42:17.180 --> 00:42:18.740
You bought a bad good.

00:42:18.740 --> 00:42:19.720
That's it.

00:42:19.720 --> 00:42:22.990
If you have an experience
that goes wrong.

00:42:22.990 --> 00:42:24.459
The bus trip
across-- I was going

00:42:24.459 --> 00:42:26.250
to say a bus trip across
India [INAUDIBLE],

00:42:26.250 --> 00:42:27.800
but since that was
a fun bus trip.

00:42:27.800 --> 00:42:31.275
But the bus trip across
India-- or Peru, or Columbia,

00:42:31.275 --> 00:42:34.684
or Thailand where
it all goes wrong.

00:42:34.684 --> 00:42:36.100
Have you all been
on one of those?

00:42:36.100 --> 00:42:39.400
The person next to you was sick,
or some other unpleasant thing

00:42:39.400 --> 00:42:41.530
was happening, the
windows wouldn't shut

00:42:41.530 --> 00:42:43.730
or they wouldn't open,
it was too hot, too

00:42:43.730 --> 00:42:45.110
cold, you were sick.

00:42:45.110 --> 00:42:45.860
It all went wrong.

00:42:45.860 --> 00:42:48.600
It was supposed to take
2 hours, it took 3 days.

00:42:48.600 --> 00:42:50.710
Have you all been
one of those trips?

00:42:50.710 --> 00:42:53.310
And how bad was it at the time?

00:42:53.310 --> 00:42:55.760
And how amazing is it now?

00:42:55.760 --> 00:42:58.450
And that's the funny
thing about experiences.

00:42:58.450 --> 00:43:01.870
If you buy an experience,
and it's really bad,

00:43:01.870 --> 00:43:03.970
it's actually brilliant.

00:43:03.970 --> 00:43:06.940
So my advice to you would be
shift from material things

00:43:06.940 --> 00:43:08.652
to experiences.

00:43:08.652 --> 00:43:10.610
It has a lot of other
knock on effects as well.

00:43:10.610 --> 00:43:13.070
The environment, for example.

00:43:13.070 --> 00:43:14.562
But yeah, those are reasons.

00:43:14.562 --> 00:43:16.020
AUDIENCE: I'm
wondering how you not

00:43:16.020 --> 00:43:18.664
get stufficated by the
stuff of experience.

00:43:18.664 --> 00:43:20.830
So for example, if you go
skiing, you have the skis.

00:43:20.830 --> 00:43:22.399
You might have the scuba gear.

00:43:22.399 --> 00:43:23.440
You have the bread maker.

00:43:23.440 --> 00:43:25.196
You have all that stuff, right?

00:43:25.196 --> 00:43:26.570
Maybe you go to
Thailand, and you

00:43:26.570 --> 00:43:28.560
buy that beautiful painting,
but you went to Peru,

00:43:28.560 --> 00:43:29.893
and you bought this other thing.

00:43:29.893 --> 00:43:31.800
All of a sudden, your
house is full of stuff,

00:43:31.800 --> 00:43:33.554
but it's all related
to experience.

00:43:33.554 --> 00:43:34.970
So how do you not
get stufficated?

00:43:34.970 --> 00:43:36.859
JAMES WALLMAN: That
is a great question.

00:43:36.859 --> 00:43:38.650
It's funny, there's a
bit in the book where

00:43:38.650 --> 00:43:40.770
I, kind of, really take that on.

00:43:40.770 --> 00:43:43.559
There's a guy in the
book called Ben Howe.

00:43:43.559 --> 00:43:44.350
He's an Australian.

00:43:44.350 --> 00:43:48.210
If you go to his house in
Adelaide in South Australia,

00:43:48.210 --> 00:43:49.610
he's got a really regular house.

00:43:49.610 --> 00:43:53.879
If anything, it's not messy,
but it's not completed.

00:43:53.879 --> 00:43:55.670
You know, you walk into
your friend's house

00:43:55.670 --> 00:43:57.010
and sometimes think, how
long have you lived here?

00:43:57.010 --> 00:43:58.350
And you think
they've been a month,

00:43:58.350 --> 00:43:59.558
but they've been there years.

00:43:59.558 --> 00:44:02.110
It's kinda that.

00:44:02.110 --> 00:44:05.320
But you go to the garage,
and you put up the, kind of,

00:44:05.320 --> 00:44:08.016
rickety door, it's
full of stuff.

00:44:08.016 --> 00:44:10.640
He's got his motorbike in there,
he's got his kite surfing kit,

00:44:10.640 --> 00:44:13.223
he's got his wind surfing kit,
he's got his rock climbing kit,

00:44:13.223 --> 00:44:14.860
he's got his skiing kit.

00:44:14.860 --> 00:44:16.230
I'm not anti stuff.

00:44:16.230 --> 00:44:18.700
The message of stuffication
is not anti stuff,

00:44:18.700 --> 00:44:20.390
it's anti too much stuff.

00:44:20.390 --> 00:44:22.550
It's anti focus on stuff.

00:44:22.550 --> 00:44:24.800
I wish I mentioned the bread
maker because that really

00:44:24.800 --> 00:44:25.380
is stuff.

00:44:25.380 --> 00:44:28.800
But anyway, the smell of fresh
bread, it's a lovely thing.

00:44:28.800 --> 00:44:33.220
But if you want to ski, you
have to have things to do that.

00:44:33.220 --> 00:44:35.662
At the same time,
a walk in the park

00:44:35.662 --> 00:44:38.120
is an experience you can have
and don't need a lot of stuff

00:44:38.120 --> 00:44:39.870
apart from feet.

00:44:39.870 --> 00:44:42.360
And if you look at statistics,
if you live near a park,

00:44:42.360 --> 00:44:44.420
you will be happier.

00:44:44.420 --> 00:44:46.070
It's just one of those facts.

00:44:46.070 --> 00:44:49.080
So and you mentioned going to
Peru and buying the painting,

00:44:49.080 --> 00:44:50.972
you don't have to
buy that painting.

00:44:50.972 --> 00:44:53.182
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:44:53.182 --> 00:44:56.870
JAMES WALLMAN: Well I've been
to Peru, I have no paintings.

00:44:56.870 --> 00:44:59.640
[INAUDIBLE] No
paintings from Peru.

00:44:59.640 --> 00:45:00.940
I have a couple of paintings.

00:45:00.940 --> 00:45:04.730
But I remember it really
well-- I heard a howler monkey,

00:45:04.730 --> 00:45:08.310
for example-- and this
was certainly in an era

00:45:08.310 --> 00:45:10.830
before I had a telephone
that could record sounds--

00:45:10.830 --> 00:45:15.130
but I can remember the sound
of that surreal howler monkey

00:45:15.130 --> 00:45:17.024
to this day.

00:45:17.024 --> 00:45:18.690
I hadn't talked about
that howler monkey

00:45:18.690 --> 00:45:21.870
for about a decade, so thank you
for bringing that back to me.

00:45:21.870 --> 00:45:24.410
But you don't need to have
stuff to have an experience.

00:45:24.410 --> 00:45:27.534
Although, the two
sometimes come together.

00:45:27.534 --> 00:45:29.450
AUDIENCE: Could there
be too many experiences?

00:45:29.450 --> 00:45:32.680
To the point where
the value of them

00:45:32.680 --> 00:45:34.820
is lessened because you're
doing so many things?

00:45:34.820 --> 00:45:36.702
I think my life has
shifted in that way.

00:45:36.702 --> 00:45:39.160
I don't have a car, I've lived
in so many different places,

00:45:39.160 --> 00:45:40.600
so I could always purge.

00:45:40.600 --> 00:45:43.720
And I'm always Tahoe
or Europe or whatever.

00:45:43.720 --> 00:45:47.330
But maybe you're searching
for something big,

00:45:47.330 --> 00:45:48.890
like bigger the next time.

00:45:48.890 --> 00:45:51.649
Could it dull what's important
and what makes you happy?

00:45:51.649 --> 00:45:52.690
JAMES WALLMAN: Thank you.

00:45:52.690 --> 00:45:54.010
It's a really good
question as well.

00:45:54.010 --> 00:45:56.260
And its really interesting
talking to people that move

00:45:56.260 --> 00:45:56.990
country a lot.

00:45:56.990 --> 00:46:00.410
They get this so quickly
because they do the country move

00:46:00.410 --> 00:46:02.820
purge all the time.

00:46:02.820 --> 00:46:05.370
And by definition of moving
from one country to another,

00:46:05.370 --> 00:46:07.000
they're appreciating
the experience

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:07.610
of going to another country.

00:46:07.610 --> 00:46:09.859
They tend to be more interested
in this kind of thing.

00:46:12.240 --> 00:46:15.630
And I've spent a couple ski
seasons in the mountains.

00:46:15.630 --> 00:46:18.160
At the end of five months
of being at a ski resort--

00:46:18.160 --> 00:46:21.740
I have to be honest-- it sort
of loses some of its fizz,

00:46:21.740 --> 00:46:23.400
compared to right
at the beginning.

00:46:23.400 --> 00:46:29.980
And for someone who's
got so many experiences,

00:46:29.980 --> 00:46:32.260
that your signs get
dulled by experiences,

00:46:32.260 --> 00:46:34.310
that is a great problem to have.

00:46:34.310 --> 00:46:35.450
Let's be really clear here.

00:46:35.450 --> 00:46:40.010
Stuffication is a
fantastic problem to have.

00:46:40.010 --> 00:46:43.940
Scarcity-- not having enough--
is a horrible problem to have,

00:46:43.940 --> 00:46:44.917
actually.

00:46:44.917 --> 00:46:47.000
And I'm not saying this
for everyone in the world.

00:46:47.000 --> 00:46:49.630
This is for rich,
Western countries.

00:46:49.630 --> 00:46:52.360
Other countries don't
have nearly the abundance

00:46:52.360 --> 00:46:56.619
that we have per capita,
but as a whole country.

00:46:56.619 --> 00:46:58.410
So stuffication is a
great problem to have.

00:46:58.410 --> 00:47:03.300
If you get to the point where
you've done wind walking,

00:47:03.300 --> 00:47:08.180
you've flown in helicopters,
you've been skiing in Kashmir,

00:47:08.180 --> 00:47:10.870
you've spent time with monkeys,
whatever it might be, right?

00:47:10.870 --> 00:47:12.995
If you've got to the point
where you're stufficated

00:47:12.995 --> 00:47:16.750
with experience, are you saying
you're at that point now?

00:47:16.750 --> 00:47:19.880
Because I'd say that is an
amazing problem to have.

00:47:26.350 --> 00:47:28.140
The thing is as well
here, is that there's

00:47:28.140 --> 00:47:31.960
an element of the material
versus the experiential choice,

00:47:31.960 --> 00:47:34.490
being a first level
heuristic-- a kind

00:47:34.490 --> 00:47:37.360
of simple way of making the
right choice-- because one

00:47:37.360 --> 00:47:41.320
of the key things about this
actually is, is it extrinsic

00:47:41.320 --> 00:47:42.640
or is it intrinsic?

00:47:42.640 --> 00:47:44.900
In terms of how you
make the decision.

00:47:44.900 --> 00:47:49.250
So if you buy material
good for yourself--

00:47:49.250 --> 00:47:51.960
So I'm not trying to show off
to you about my break maker.

00:47:51.960 --> 00:47:54.970
I really mean that-- I'm buying
the bread maker because we

00:47:54.970 --> 00:47:56.580
discussed it and
we think we will

00:47:56.580 --> 00:47:58.154
enjoy having that experience.

00:47:58.154 --> 00:48:00.070
And fresh bread is really
expensive in London,

00:48:00.070 --> 00:48:01.769
by the way.

00:48:01.769 --> 00:48:03.560
I don't want to fixate
on this bread maker.

00:48:03.560 --> 00:48:05.110
But we the decision for us.

00:48:05.110 --> 00:48:08.170
We're not doing as an extrinsic
thing to say, hey, look at us,

00:48:08.170 --> 00:48:09.796
we bought a bread maker.

00:48:09.796 --> 00:48:11.670
And it can be the with
same with experiences.

00:48:11.670 --> 00:48:13.290
You know those
people who will go

00:48:13.290 --> 00:48:15.310
to the place to go on holiday.

00:48:15.310 --> 00:48:17.632
They'll read a magazine and
go that's the place I have

00:48:17.632 --> 00:48:19.090
to go on holiday
because then I can

00:48:19.090 --> 00:48:20.704
tell people I've been there.

00:48:20.704 --> 00:48:21.620
You know these people?

00:48:21.620 --> 00:48:24.670
You all have friends like
that, or acquaintances?

00:48:24.670 --> 00:48:26.930
You don't get as
much pleasure if you

00:48:26.930 --> 00:48:30.790
buy that experiential good
for an extrinsic reason,

00:48:30.790 --> 00:48:33.070
than if you buy it for
an intrinsic reason.

00:48:33.070 --> 00:48:37.100
But-- and this is why I like
the distinction between material

00:48:37.100 --> 00:48:39.720
and experiential
decisions-- even if you

00:48:39.720 --> 00:48:44.730
buy that experiential good
to show off to other people--

00:48:44.730 --> 00:48:47.690
to tell people who you are other
than doing it for yourself--

00:48:47.690 --> 00:48:49.820
you'll still be
doing that thing.

00:48:49.820 --> 00:48:52.210
Let's say you
decided that you have

00:48:52.210 --> 00:48:54.410
to ski in Squaw Valley--
for the sake of argument--

00:48:54.410 --> 00:48:55.650
now there's snow
there, you've decided

00:48:55.650 --> 00:48:57.858
that you have to do that so
you can tell your friends

00:48:57.858 --> 00:48:58.850
you've done it.

00:48:58.850 --> 00:49:01.440
You'll still be skiing
in Squaw Valley.

00:49:01.440 --> 00:49:02.540
Do you see what I mean?

00:49:02.540 --> 00:49:04.609
So that's why I think
that distinction works.

00:49:04.609 --> 00:49:07.150
But if you get to that point
the stufficate with experiences,

00:49:07.150 --> 00:49:08.590
let's definitely talk.

00:49:08.590 --> 00:49:12.250
AUDIENCE: Isn't the risk
that we are replacing

00:49:12.250 --> 00:49:14.320
one problem with just another?

00:49:14.320 --> 00:49:20.280
With stuffing our lives with
experiences and actually,

00:49:20.280 --> 00:49:24.270
our time is much more limited
than this pace we have.

00:49:24.270 --> 00:49:30.500
So is it a better way to
live your life actually,

00:49:30.500 --> 00:49:34.600
or should we actually look
for even another answer.

00:49:34.600 --> 00:49:39.210
Make time to think and not
just to get our experiences

00:49:39.210 --> 00:49:43.229
going for holidays, new
restaurants, and so on.

00:49:43.229 --> 00:49:45.020
JAMES WALLMAN: It's a
really good question.

00:49:45.020 --> 00:49:47.290
Thank you.

00:49:47.290 --> 00:49:49.600
Often when I'm
explaining this-- and I

00:49:49.600 --> 00:49:55.460
give a talk on this-- I tend to
talk about things that you do,

00:49:55.460 --> 00:49:56.290
actively do.

00:49:56.290 --> 00:49:58.510
Because probably, it's
easier to visualize,

00:49:58.510 --> 00:50:00.770
and it makes it a bit more
interesting to listen to.

00:50:00.770 --> 00:50:05.090
But sitting, thinking
is an experience,

00:50:05.090 --> 00:50:06.570
as far as I'm concerned.

00:50:06.570 --> 00:50:09.700
And I don't think
that we're replacing

00:50:09.700 --> 00:50:11.069
one problem with another.

00:50:11.069 --> 00:50:13.360
I think we're replacing one
problem with something that

00:50:13.360 --> 00:50:15.670
is exponentially better.

00:50:15.670 --> 00:50:19.620
And I agree with you that
we only have so much time.

00:50:19.620 --> 00:50:22.490
Experiences take time.

00:50:22.490 --> 00:50:24.600
But that's life.

00:50:24.600 --> 00:50:26.389
And the choice of
experiences that you do

00:50:26.389 --> 00:50:28.555
are the choice of what you
do with your time, that's

00:50:28.555 --> 00:50:29.971
what you do with
your life, right?

00:50:29.971 --> 00:50:35.860
As opposed to you're saying that
there's more space for stuff

00:50:35.860 --> 00:50:38.590
and therefore, we should
spend money on stuff

00:50:38.590 --> 00:50:41.200
because we've got lots of space.

00:50:41.200 --> 00:50:44.650
If you look at demographics and
the urbanization of the world,

00:50:44.650 --> 00:50:45.754
we have less space.

00:50:45.754 --> 00:50:48.170
There's seven billion people
now, it might be nine billion

00:50:48.170 --> 00:50:51.200
by 2050.

00:50:51.200 --> 00:50:53.280
More people living in
cities, less space.

00:50:53.280 --> 00:50:55.203
So I think we have
less space, but I

00:50:55.203 --> 00:50:59.159
think the most important part
of your question was about time.

00:50:59.159 --> 00:51:00.700
The other thing
about experientialism

00:51:00.700 --> 00:51:04.500
is a focus on what
you do with your time.

00:51:04.500 --> 00:51:05.760
It's about your experiences.

00:51:05.760 --> 00:51:07.510
And what could be more
important than what

00:51:07.510 --> 00:51:10.700
you do with your time, as
opposed to the stuff you buy?

00:51:10.700 --> 00:51:16.580
So in terms of the refocus from
material things to experiences,

00:51:16.580 --> 00:51:18.880
I think there's a refocus
on life and what matters.

00:51:18.880 --> 00:51:20.680
AUDIENCE: My
question is about how

00:51:20.680 --> 00:51:25.580
do you with people becoming
less and less materialistic--

00:51:25.580 --> 00:51:31.720
compared to even 40 years
ago, as Mr. Inglehart said--

00:51:31.720 --> 00:51:34.510
how do you think it's going
to influence job market?

00:51:34.510 --> 00:51:37.760
Because not all of
us can make a living

00:51:37.760 --> 00:51:39.920
writing programs
or writing books.

00:51:39.920 --> 00:51:44.090
Some of us, for example,
enjoy creating stuff.

00:51:44.090 --> 00:51:45.559
Sewing or something like that.

00:51:45.559 --> 00:51:47.350
So if we're going to
be less materialistic,

00:51:47.350 --> 00:51:49.850
is that going to become
a problem for people

00:51:49.850 --> 00:51:53.830
who are making their
living producing stuff

00:51:53.830 --> 00:51:57.175
and selling stuff?

00:51:57.175 --> 00:51:59.860
JAMES WALLMAN: It's a
very interesting aspect

00:51:59.860 --> 00:52:04.960
of the problem of materialism
and the defining problem

00:52:04.960 --> 00:52:05.710
stuffication.

00:52:05.710 --> 00:52:08.560
The shift from the material
to experiential economy

00:52:08.560 --> 00:52:11.830
is what's going to happen
to some industries.

00:52:11.830 --> 00:52:15.430
With any change, there are
winners and there are losers.

00:52:15.430 --> 00:52:18.630
You ever heard of a guy called
Ned Ludd, who led the Luddites?

00:52:18.630 --> 00:52:20.240
Ever heard the
phrase, the Luddites?

00:52:20.240 --> 00:52:23.180
So when the Industrial
Revolution got going in the UK,

00:52:23.180 --> 00:52:27.090
this guy in the north of England
smashed some of the machines.

00:52:27.090 --> 00:52:28.840
He may have just been
drunk-- it turns out

00:52:28.840 --> 00:52:30.877
he may have not been
protesting at all.

00:52:30.877 --> 00:52:32.960
Apparently, if you look
into it, it's really odd--

00:52:32.960 --> 00:52:34.710
but he became their
hero and they and they

00:52:34.710 --> 00:52:37.220
called themselves Luddites
because those machines were

00:52:37.220 --> 00:52:41.104
taking away their jobs, and
they were hugely concerned.

00:52:41.104 --> 00:52:42.770
Did that stop the
Industrial Revolution?

00:52:42.770 --> 00:52:43.220
No.

00:52:43.220 --> 00:52:45.261
Should it have stopped
the Industrial Revolution?

00:52:45.261 --> 00:52:45.810
Not at all.

00:52:45.810 --> 00:52:47.685
Because it was the
Industrial Revolution that

00:52:47.685 --> 00:52:51.360
led to the consumer evolution
that gave us abundance,

00:52:51.360 --> 00:52:54.200
that gave us everything
that we have today.

00:52:54.200 --> 00:52:56.990
So there will definitely be
changes in the job market.

00:52:56.990 --> 00:53:00.510
And definitely be changes
in terms of what we value.

00:53:00.510 --> 00:53:02.472
And I think it will
change for the better.

00:53:02.472 --> 00:53:03.930
You think about 3D
printing, what's

00:53:03.930 --> 00:53:08.610
3D printing going to do for all
those people who make stuff?

00:53:08.610 --> 00:53:11.040
When you can 3D
print it at home,

00:53:11.040 --> 00:53:13.380
it's going to completely
change that market, isn't it?

00:53:13.380 --> 00:53:16.210
Why you going to have loads of
factories of people producing

00:53:16.210 --> 00:53:19.680
plastic goods, when you
can print it at home?

00:53:19.680 --> 00:53:22.050
So the world is
changing, anyway.

00:53:22.050 --> 00:53:28.100
And what I'm hoping-- this is
my belief-- what materialism

00:53:28.100 --> 00:53:31.350
did for standards of living
in the 20th century, which

00:53:31.350 --> 00:53:34.120
was just revolutionized them
in a way that just had never

00:53:34.120 --> 00:53:36.200
happened in the whole
of human existence.

00:53:36.200 --> 00:53:40.300
I think experientialism could
do that for quality of life

00:53:40.300 --> 00:53:41.920
in the 21st century.

00:53:41.920 --> 00:53:43.810
We could end up in
this age of leisure,

00:53:43.810 --> 00:53:46.840
which [INAUDIBLE] talked
about back in the '30s.

00:53:46.840 --> 00:53:47.931
That's what I hope.

00:53:47.931 --> 00:53:48.430
SPEAKER: OK.

00:53:48.430 --> 00:53:51.570
Why don't we thank
our speaker today.

